&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>A &lt;a href="https://www.fr.redhat.com/red_hat_network/" rel="external" target="_blank">Red Hat Satellite&lt;svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">&lt;path fill="currentColor" d="M14 5c-.552 0-1-.448-1-1s.448-1 1-1h6c.552 0 1 .448 1 1v6c0 .552-.448 1-1 1s-1-.448-1-1v-3.586l-7.293 7.293c-.391.39-1.024.39-1.414 0-.391-.391-.391-1.024 0-1.414l7.293-7.293h-3.586zm-9 2c-.552 0-1 .448-1 1v11c0 .552.448 1 1 1h11c.552 0 1-.448 1-1v-4.563c0-.552.448-1 1-1s1 .448 1 1v4.563c0 1.657-1.343 3-3 3h-11c-1.657 0-3-1.343-3-3v-11c0-1.657 1.343-3 3-3h4.563c.552 0 1 .448 1 1s-.448 1-1 1h-4.563z"/>&lt;/svg>&lt;/a> server is a solution that allows you to automatically deploy Red Hat OS via PXE/DHCP. You can then manage different installation profiles, manage updates, and perform a variety of simplified administrative tasks.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Setting up a WiFi Hotspot</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Monter_un_Hotspot_Wifi/</link><pubDate>Fri, 23 May 2008 07:05:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Monter_un_Hotspot_Wifi/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>One of the things, if not THE thing I was dying to do in my new apartment, was to set up a real hotspot, as I explained in the two news posts below. Well, it&amp;rsquo;s now up and running. I don&amp;rsquo;t know yet if I&amp;rsquo;ll make a full article about it or if I&amp;rsquo;ll just give tips as I go along, but in the meantime, here&amp;rsquo;s what it looks like:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Setting up DHCP Failover</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Mise_en_place_d'un_DHCP_Failover/</link><pubDate>Tue, 06 Nov 2007 18:42:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Mise_en_place_d'un_DHCP_Failover/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>I&amp;rsquo;ve been running a DHCP server on my home network for eons now, and today I decided I&amp;rsquo;d move it on to my OpenBSD firewall cluster. It probably really shouldn&amp;rsquo;t be there but I already run a handful of other internal services there, like DNS, and NTP.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>I assume you already have a working &lt;a href="https://www.openbsd.org/faq/faq6.html#DHCP" rel="external" target="_blank">dhcpd configuration&lt;svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">&lt;path fill="currentColor" d="M14 5c-.552 0-1-.448-1-1s.448-1 1-1h6c.552 0 1 .448 1 1v6c0 .552-.448 1-1 1s-1-.448-1-1v-3.586l-7.293 7.293c-.391.39-1.024.39-1.414 0-.391-.391-.391-1.024 0-1.414l7.293-7.293h-3.586zm-9 2c-.552 0-1 .448-1 1v11c0 .552.448 1 1 1h11c.552 0 1-.448 1-1v-4.563c0-.552.448-1 1-1s1 .448 1 1v4.563c0 1.657-1.343 3-3 3h-11c-1.657 0-3-1.343-3-3v-11c0-1.657 1.343-3 3-3h4.563c.552 0 1 .448 1 1s-.448 1-1 1h-4.563z"/>&lt;/svg>&lt;/a> for your single server, if you don&amp;rsquo;t, then you can get a basic DHCP configuration from the OpenBSD FAQ.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Configuring a Local Network on Debian and Ubuntu</title><link>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Configuration_d%27un_r%C3%A9seau_local_sur_Debian_et_Ubuntu/</link><pubDate>Wed, 18 Apr 2007 14:03:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://wiki.deimos.fr/Configuration_d%27un_r%C3%A9seau_local_sur_Debian_et_Ubuntu/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction &lt;a href="#introduction" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>Not always easy to remember what to put in these damn files, right? Here are some simple examples.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="configuring-network-interfaces">Configuring Network Interfaces &lt;a href="#configuring-network-interfaces" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>Edit the file &lt;code>/etc/network/interfaces&lt;/code>.&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="static-ip-addressing">Static IP Addressing &lt;a href="#static-ip-addressing" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>&lt;p>For example, here&amp;rsquo;s how I configure my eth0 interface:&lt;/p>



 
 
 

 
 
 
 

 

 &lt;div class="prism-codeblock ">
 &lt;pre id="b464be6" class="language-bash ">
 &lt;code>auto lo eth0
iface lo inet loopback

# Interface eth0
iface eth0 inet static
 address 192.168.0.1
 netmask 255.255.255.0
 broadcast 192.168.0.255
 network 192.168.0.0
 gateway 192.168.0.138&lt;/code>
 &lt;/pre>
 &lt;/div>
